Photocatalytic technology can sustainably convert solar energy into electric energy to treat polluted water, which is regarded as a sustainable and promising purification technology [6]. Under light excitation, electrons and holes are generated and gathered at the conduction band (ECB
                     ) and valence-band (EVB
                     ), respectively [7,8]. The photogenerated electrons facilitate the reduction of Cr(VI) to low-toxicity trivalent chromium (Cr(III)), which is an essential trace element for humans [9]. Meanwhile, the holes can directly or indirectly degrade CBZ [10]. Therefore, photocatalytic technology exhibits the potential for simultaneous CBZ degradation and Cr(VI) reduction. However, the performance is limited by the weak light absorption capability, unacceptable separation efficiency of the electron-hole pairs, and poor photoelectric conversion proficiency of the electrode materials [11].

The surface morphologies of the prepared photoanodes were observed by FESEM (Fig. 2
                        ). Regular nanotube arrays and uniform nano-rings were observed, and the inner and outer diameters were 120 nm and 140 nm (nanotube wall: 10 nm), exhibiting typical TNAs morphology (Fig. 2a). For CQDs, the diameter was in the range of 4–7 nm, as confirmed by the HRTEM image, and the lattice spacing was 0.23 nm, corresponding to the (100) plane (Fig. 3
                        ). In the presence of 10% (vol/vol) MPA, the CQDs were well-linked and adsorbed on the surface of the nanotube wall (Fig. 2b). Meanwhile, an apparent aggregation phenomenon was observed, forming 10–20 nm CQD nanoparticles without blocking the TNAs channels. In addition, a layer of thin film was observed on the TP surface (Fig. 2c), and a well-ordered nanotube array could still be observed. The results indicated that both dipping and the in-situ polymerisation of aniline processes barely affected the TNAs structure. Compared to the TP, a significantly thick film layer was observed on the TCP surface under the same in-situ electro-polymerisation conditions (Fig. 2d). According to the CV curves (Fig. S1), all peaks were significantly higher in the TCP than TP at the same cycling number, and the peak intensity gradually decreased with increasing cycling number, revealing that the polymerisation amount of aniline gradually decreased. In addition, the peak centre exhibited a slight shift owing to the presence of SO4
                        2-. The results revealed that CQDs contributed to the polymerisation of aniline. In addition, PVA-rGO exhibited a porous structure (Fig. S6), representing a high specific surface area and strong adsorption capability.
